Although AGAR is a substitute for gelatin, curiously, it must be handled differently--indeed oppositely--than gelatin: gelatin must be soaked in cold water, then added to the hot mixture at the end, and don't let it come to a boil, or the thickening property of the gelatin will be destroyed; agar, OTOH, is added to the cold liquid at the start, and must come to a full, rolling boil for about 30 seconds to cause it to thicken. The texture is quite different, too, and some people miss the distinctive "jiggle" of gelatin.

